SECTION 1. The Juvenile and Domestic Relations Court.- There shall be a Juvenile and Domestic Relations Court for the City of Baguio and the Province of Benguet, with its seat at the Municipality of La Trinidad, Province of Benguet to be presided by a judge who shall have the experience, recognizable attitude or demonstrated ability in dealing with cases involving children and families, and shall further possess the same qualifications, enjoy the same privileges and receive the same salary as judges of the Courts of First Instance, He shall be appointed by the President of the Philippines, with the consent of the Commission on Appointments.

Jurisdiction

.âThe provisions of the Judiciary Act of 1948, as amended, to the contrary notwithstanding, the court shall have exclusive original jurisdiction to hear and decide the following cases:

Criminal cases cognizable by the City Court of Baguio and the Courts of First Instance, within the territorial limits of Baguio City and the Province of Benguet wherein the accused is under sixteen years of age at the time of the trial;

Cases involving custody, guardianship, adoption, paternity and acknowledgment;

Cases involving custody, guardianship, adoption, paternity and acknowledgment;

Annulment of marriages, legal separation of spouses and action for support;

Proceedings brought under the provisions of articles one hundred sixteen, two hundred twenty-five, two hundred fifty-one and three hundred thirty-two of the Civil Code;

Petitions for the declaration of absence and for the change of name;

Actions for the separation of property of spouse; and

Proceedings affecting a dependent or neglected child, as hereinafter defined.

The court shall likewise have such incidental powers as are originally possessed by Courts of First Instance.

If any question involving any of the above matters should arise as an incident in any case pending in the ordinary courts, said incident shall be determined in the main case.
